<h3 id="yes-im-a-serial-planner-switcher-that-is-the-plan">Yes, Iâ€™m a serial planner-switcher; that <span class="small-caps">IS</span> the plan</h3>
<p>Iâ€™ve switched planners â€” both analog and digital â€” part way through the year more times than I can remember, but never with one this pricey. Itâ€™s a lovely, lovely planner and I still like it very much yet here I am, feeling that old familiar itch. An itch sparked by one of the partially filled Moleskine Cahier notebooks in my notebook box.</p>
<p>At the front of this old book is an experimental spread I drew up roughly in 2023 to try out some hand-drawn calendars. It is simple, rustic, and unpretentious, and the very essence of uncomplicated freedom I was â€” and am â€” drawn to.</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/63529348-4817-440d-bf02-162525140da8.png" alt="An open A5 Moleskine Cahier notebook being held up at an angle, showing a roughly hand drawn month spreading over both pages" width="1332" height="1312"> <em>The old layout that de-throned a Wonderland222, with my Mumâ€™s handmade quilt in the background. I was into European-style number ones at the time, apparently</em></p>
<hr>
<p>When a new idea grabs me, I have the tendency to sweep the table and start afresh. This is why I love the plain text life so much and why Iâ€™m drawn to simple analog systems: one can butterfly away with minimal disruption to the flow of things.</p>
<h3 id="this-is-how-it-works">This is how it works</h3>
<p>My notebook setup (for the next few months at least) consists of two Cahiers and a wad of single-sided scrap paper, all in a Paper Saver notebook. Two ancient leather Quiver pen holders serve nicely to carry an average black ballpoint pen (current model is from Typo, aka Cotton On in Australia), a Uni Kuru Toga self-rotating 0.5mm mechanical pencil, and an eraser pen whose body I wish came in more earthy tones.</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/8998067d-fc9d-45ed-bd22-ad99c5f47881.png" alt="Black notebook, closed, with two tan leather pen holders strapped to the outside. thereâ€™s a bright blue eraser pen with a white cap and a mechanical pencil in the double pen holder on the front of the book, and a tan coloured clicky ballpoint pen in the holder that cradles the spine." width="1156" height="1226"></p>
<p><em>The fraying additional ribbon bookmark was cut from the inside shoulder seam of one of my jumpers (sweatersâ€Š/â€Špullovers). I may get around to neatening the edge one of these days.</em></p>
<hr>
<p>The straps of the Quiver pen holders also keep two 80-page Moleskines in place at the front and back of the book. One of the Cahiers contains 6 monthly spreads followed by 26 weekly spreads, and the other is for general note making when I feel like writing in a book. The scrap paper is for throw-away scribblings, studying French vocab and grammar, drawing diagrams to give to other people, and for a pleasant sense of environmental responsibility.</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/e349f5e3-a1f6-468c-8764-e8c0cbd5fa33.png" alt="Three photos showing two notebooks being held in place at the font and back of a Paper Saver folder, with a stack of A4 paper folded in half threaded through a metal bar running along the spine of the folder. Two black bookmark ribbons are visible." width="2698" height="1050"> <em>My two favourite Moleskine Cahier colours: black and myrtle green</em></p>
<hr>
<p>I view the non-planner Cahier as a type of <a href="https://ellanew.com/obtf"><span class="small-caps">OBTF</span> (One Big Text File)</a>. The premise is the same: add the date, then write whatever you want. Iâ€™m making use of the <a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl/126-dash-plus-system-in-obtf-and-analog-notes">dash plus system</a>, starting every note with a dash and modifying that dash to classify notes as needed.</p>
<h3 id="wonderland222-and-moleskine-pros-and-cons">Wonderland222 and Moleskine pros and cons</h3>
<p>The Wonderland222 has â€”</p>
<ul>
<li>âž• Understated grey grids with Hobonichi-sized squares</li>
<li>âž• Space for year, quarter, month, week, and daily plans</li>
<li>âž• Dates already in place</li>
<li>âž• Thin, watercolour and ink friendly Tomoe River paper</li>
<li>âž– âž• Months spaced out amongst the weekly planning pages (not my preference)</li>
<li>âž– American holidays (many arenâ€™t accurate or relevant in Australia)</li>
<li>âž– A hefty price tag</li>
<li>âž– Pressure to keep using the book because of the price (mustnâ€™t waste that investment, sigh)</li>
</ul>
<p>The Moleskine Cahier has â€”</p>
<ul>
<li>âž• 6mm ruled lines that arenâ€™t (usually) too dark or too light</li>
<li>âž• Rounded corners</li>
<li>âž• A cardboard cover that feels nice to the touch (unlike some shiny versions Iâ€™ve lived to regret buying)</li>
<li>âž• Card pocket at the back of the book</li>
<li>âž• Perforated pages at the back</li>
<li>âž• A reasonable price tag (I can get four for under AU$30â€Š/â€ŠUS$20)</li>
<li>âž• No pressure to perform or fear of wastage (Iâ€™ve dipped in and out of these books countless times over the years)</li>
<li>âž– âž• Stitched binding down the middle looks nice from the outside but means that pages near the front and back of the book are a teeny bit narrower than those around the centre</li>
<li>âž– âž• No preprinted dates, structures or page numbers â€” an advantage when you have your own ideas in mind</li>
<li>âž– âž• Moleskine pages are narrower than <span class="small-caps">A4</span>, but when taking a monthly or weekly grid right to the edge of the page the difference is negligible.</li>
<li>âž– Paper that can handle ball point and gel pens, but not wet inks</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="blinded-by-the-brand-no-way">Blinded by the brand? No way</h3>
<p>Thereâ€™s something about the combination of features in the Cahier that works for me. I have not been able to find a comparable alternative anywhere else and believe me, Iâ€™ve looked.</p>
<p>No, Iâ€™m not blinded by the Moleskine brand and its associations with creative minds from a bygone era. There really <em>is</em> something special in the 6 mm ruled lines, the rounded corners, the feel of the cover, and those lovely chunky stitches down the middle!</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/a1fd24b0-2e98-43cf-bd57-e3df9f257f92.png" alt="Two side by side photos of Moleskine Cahier notebooks showing a weekly and monthly spread respectively, hand drawn in black ballpoint pen and pencil" width="2262" height="1458"> <em>Hand drawn calendar layouts. Please ignore that mysterious phantom <span class="small-caps">TABS</span> artifact that I couldnâ€™t get to disappear before taking the screenshot.</em></p>
<hr>
<p>And so this week Iâ€™ve lent into the delicious insanity of creating my own planner entirely by hand, right there in a fresh Moleskine Cahier. Drawing up a week or two at a time while watching <span class="small-caps">TV</span> or listening to podcasts means it hasnâ€™t been arduous; more of a soothing activity that helps quieten my brain monkeys in much the same way as knitting or sewing something simple.</p>
<div class="right margin">
There will be no failures, no right or wrong, simply data that will tell me something I did not know before
</div>
<p>Cahiers only have 80 pages (40 sheets) in them, meaning Iâ€™ll need two to cover a full year. Perhaps in 6 months Iâ€™ll be onto something else, but thatâ€™s the beauty of a flexible system! Youâ€™re never fenced in.</p>
<p>The structure of monthly and weekly pages echo the approach followed in the Wonderland222, and other <span class="small-caps">A5</span> vertical left-to-right weekly planners. Itâ€™s a simple and effective way to plan the week.</p>
<h3 id="a-joyful-tiny-stationery-experiment">A joyful tiny stationery experiment</h3>
<p>Anne-Laure le Cunff would call this a <a href="https://nesslabs.com/book" target="_blank">tiny experiment</a>, because thatâ€™s what it is: a happy, curiosity-driven exercise in seeing what happens when I use this kind of analog calendar.</p>
<p>How will I respond to it over time? Will I miss the grid of the Wonderland222? Will seeing my own hand as a foundation for planning focus me more on the work, or be a distraction? Will my gut welcome the hand drawn layouts each morning before my brain has switched into analytical mode, or rebel against them? I can hardly wait to find out!</p>
<p>There will be no failures, no right or wrong, simply data that will tell me something I did not know before. And that data will shape what comes next. Now that Iâ€™m aware of shiny object syndrome and have learned how to keep it from changing the overall trajectory of my productivity, exercises like this are a mind-refreshing, fun reset! (<a href="https://ellanew.com/2020-08-26-i-was-a-task-management-app-addict">Read about the journey</a>)</p>
